Process states.

In a process listing, the state column shows a single letter telling you what the process is currently doing, and five states are worth knowing. The letter capital-r means running: either on a see-pee-you right now, or runnable and waiting its turn for one. Capital-s means sleeping: waiting for some event, like input or a timer or a network packet, and this is where most idle processes sit. Capital-d means uninterruptible sleep, usually waiting on the kernel for disk activity. Capital-t means stopped, paused by a signal or a debugger. And capital-z means zombie: finished, but its parent has not yet collected its exit status.

A few things follow from this in practice. Almost every process is sleeping most of the time, and that is perfectly healthy; sleeping just means waiting. The running state does not mean actively on a core this instant, only that the process is ready to run, so on a busy machine many processes can be runnable at once, queueing for the see-pee-you.

The state to respect is capital-d. A process stuck there is waiting on the kernel and cannot be killed, not even with the strongest signal, because it is mid-way through a kernel operation. It is almost always caused by hung disk or network storage, or a faulty driver. If you see persistent capital-d, investigate the storage system; a reboot clears it but hides the real cause. A single zombie, by contrast, is harmless; it holds only a process I-D and an exit code, waiting to be collected. Zombies become a problem only in large numbers, which points to a parent program that has a bug and is not collecting its children. You will also see small trailing modifiers on the state, such as a plus sign for a foreground process or an s for a session leader, so a sleeping foreground session leader, which is what your interactive shell looks like, shows up as capital-s, s, plus.
